      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "having opened, etc",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) A beginning studiously made is great part of a great matter. In commencing narrations of great and deliberate affairs, Scripture uses the phrases, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "He turned his shoulders, He moved his feet, He raised his eyes, He opened His mouth",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". See ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 10:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Here the fountain began to pour forth water. Cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 13:35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐδίδασκεν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "He taught",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") He instructed by doctrine, by consolation, by exhortation, by precept.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "αὐτοὺς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "them",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") the disciples. For He addresses these, in the hearing of the multitudes;[168] see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 7:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The Evangelists have transcribed at full length two discourses of our Lord, as models of all the rest; the one delivered publicly at the commencement of His ministry, that namely which we are now considering; the other privately at its conclusion, recorded in John 13-16. Our Lord’s object in the present discourse is to teach true righteousness (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 63:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "): and He also declares at the same time, that He came to establish the Law and the Prophets, and exposes the spurious character of the righteousness of the Scribes and Pharisees. In the exordium, there is firstly, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
